Explanation:
- I found a single router route defined in this file: router.post('/', (req, res) => { ... }). The path is the literal string '/'.
- The handler is an anonymous inline arrow function defined in the same file (so implementationPresent: true). Inside that handler the file-upload middleware (uploadSingleImage) is invoked and the response is constructed here.
- The path is a full literal path string in the source (isPathStringLiteral: true) and is not derived from any naming convention supported by the framework (isPathFromNamingConvention: false).
- The path is not a prefix (isPrefix: false) â€” it is the route string used for this POST handler (note: when this router is mounted in the application it will be combined with the mount path, but within this file the route string is the full literal provided to router.post).
- This is an API endpoint for uploading an image and is part of the REST API surface (isRestful: true), and it is not a testing-only route (isTesting: false).
- I did not include middleware or helper functions (e.g., uploadSingleImage, storage, fileFilter) as separate API entries because they are not bound to a path in this file.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.
